column168: On October 6, 2014 at 07:30 ET, a 55-gallon drum containing UN2056 tetrahydrofuran was punctured by a fork-lift blade at 90 North Plains Industrial Road, Wallingford, CT. The puncture occurred during the loading phase and approximately 25 gallons was released to the trailer floor and concrete parking area below. An environmental contractor was dispatched to the site along with the local fire department for cleanup operations. Absorbents were worked into the release thoroughly and was then picked up and placed into over-pack drums for proper disposal.

On 10/12/14 at approximately 5:10 p.m. Eric Cervantes was hauling equipment from Oxnard CA to Cantua Creek CA. EE stated he was driving north on I5 through Castaic CA when he heard what he thought was an air leak. EE stated that he checked his gauges on his dash and they all appeared to be fine. EE stated that he pulled his truck over to the side of the Highway and stepped out of his vehicle to check where the air was coming from. EE stated that he walked up between the truck and the trailer to check the airlines when he got exposed to ammonia anhydrous. EE evacuated the exposed area and immediately called 911 because he had trouble breathing. EE then contacted Mashburn Transportation Services, Inc. Emergency personnel arrived to the location and shut down the traffic on the highway. An Ambulance escorted the EE to Henry Mayo Memorial Hospital in Valencia, Ca. to be checked for chemical exposure. EE was treated and released from the hospital with in a couple of hours. Once the HAZMAT crew showed up to the scene they suited up and went into the exposed area. The HAZMAT crew found that a pipe fitting was leaking the ammonia anhydrous. Once it stopped leaking the HAZMAT crew deemed it was safe for personnel to re-enter the area based upon gas readings. Lanes 1,2, & 3 were then re-opened. Nunes Cooling (owners of equipment) sent a mechanic to fix the cracked pipe fitting. After removing the pipe fitting and replacing it with a plug the emergency personnel/ HAZMAT team was able to release the vehicle from the highway and drive it to the next exit of the highway in order to replace another fitting similar so it doesn't crack while in transit. Once the repairs were complete the vehicle was then released to Mashburn Transportation Services, Inc.
column169: Change fitting design, so that the weight of the piping is not resting on a single pipe. The weight of the piping design and the vibrations of the road is what caused the main support pipe to crack while in transport.     Or    Remove the piping while in transport and replace the piping with a plug.

At 0300 ET hours, Mike Hart of R&L Carriers contacted ERTS regarding the release of approximately 3 ( three) gallons of a UN1866 RESIN SOLUTION from a 55 (fifty-five) gallon metal drum to the rear of a trailer at the Ellenwood GA terminal. At the time of this report, no drains, soils or waterways were reported as being impacted. At this time, no regulatory reporting is required, Terminal personnel reported that the drum was forked by a tow motor driver resulting in the release. ERTS has dispatched a network contractor, Hulls Enviro of Hiram, GA to respond to the site with an estimated ETA of 90 minutes. The shipper is AOC LLC.The contractor reports that approximately 3 gallons was released to the side of the drum and floor of trailer. Clean up operations are underway. They will over pack the damaged drum and clean the trailer floor and other impacted cargo. The contractor reports that clean up operations are completed. They have over-packed the damaged drum and will leave on site for terminal OS&D to manage. 1-55 gallon drum of wastes were generated consisting of contaminated absorbents, rags and misc debris. All wastes were collected, containerized and taken by contractor for disposal. The contractor is departing the site

column168: On the morning of Tuesday, October 7th, Fuel truck 3006 was loaded with the following: Tank #1-800 gal of Ultra-low sulfur diesel, clear, Tank #2-650 gal of gasoline with less than 10% ethanol, Tank #3- 550 gal of ultra-low sulfur diesel dyed, Tank #4-550 gal of ultra-low sulfur diesel, clear, Tank #5-450 gal of ultra-low sulfur diesel clear. After deliveries 250 gal of dyed diesel and 275 of clear diesel had been dispensed. The driver's last delivery prior to the accident was to a farmer in a combine in a field on Rocky Ford Road.  Rocky Ford Road is a narrow tar and chat road and at or about 1000 hours the driver proceeded at 30 to 35 mph until he approached a 90 degree turn. The driver slowed to negotiate the turn and proceeded east toward Aviston Road. At that point Rocky Ford Road has a descending west to east slope and a culvert which crosses under the road. In addition, a pick-up truck was approaching from the east. The driver then slowed further and attempted to move to the south shoulder to allow the pick-up to pass. Just after the culvert the right rear tires left the roadway and the driver tried to slow the vehicle and make corrections.  By this time the pick-up had passed by while truck 3006 slowed either to under 5 mph or a complete stop. The driver is not certain which is correct. Regardless, the driver felt the truck lurch forward and then backward before beginning a slow roll-over onto the passenger side on the south shoulder of Rocky Ford Road. The vehicle traveled nearly 240 feet on the shoulder before the accident.  The driver was wearing his seatbelt and was uninjured except for sore ribs and a bruise on his right knee. After the accident the driver contacted the Breese facility manager, Mr. Tim Richter, who then contacted the local authorities and the Gateway FS Fuel Department Manager. One unit each from the Trenton Police Department and the Clinton County Sheriff's Department arrived to investigate. Mr. Richter arrived about 30 to 45 minutes after the accident as did the Fuel Dept. Manager. The Company Safety Coordinator was contacted by the Fuel Dept Manager at about 1045 hours. Petroff Brothers Wrecking was contacted and a unit dispatched to the scene.
column169: In the future all Gateway FS drivers shall be instructed to determine a safe point at which their vehicles can either stop or safely move aside onto a solid shoulder, driveway, etc. when on roads where traffic in either direction may be impeded by Gateway FS equipment. Said equipment includes but is not limited to fertilizer spreaders, fuel trucks, LP Trucks, service vehicles, or vehicles pulling grain augers, nurse tanks, etc.

column168: A BNSF yard switch crew reported tank car NATX 38341 emanating a commodity odor after observing liquid sloshing from its manway closure. NATX 38341 was cordoned-off in the railyard and appropriate notifications were initiated. At 1330 hrs. CDT, 10/01/2014. UPRR hazardous material responders arrived and inspected NATX 38341. The responders reported that one manway securement eyebolt was hanging (not applied on the manway cover) and the other 7 manway securement eyebolt nuts were less than tool tight. Responders applied the hanging eyebolt and properly tool tightened all manway securement eyebolt nuts. The small amount of spillage around the manway nozzle evaporated and no ground impact from spillage was reported. No further commodity release was reported during NATX 38341's subsequent movements in the railyard.

column168: AT 2010 ET hours, Rosa Behn of R&L Carriers contacted ERTS regarding the release of an unknown amount of battery acid UN2794 BATTERIES WET FILLED with ACID from a unknown amount of batteries to the trailer floor and adjacent asphalt parking lot at the McDonald's in Altamont, il. At the time of this report, no drains, soils or waterways were reported as being impacted. At this time, no regulatory reporting is required. The caller stated the driver noticed a liquid leaking from the trailer. The caller advised that the driver crawled over a fully loaded trailer to observe the release from the batteries due to a suspected load shift. ERTS has dispatched a network contractor ( EMA of ST Louis, MO ) to respond.The contractor reports arriving on site. the contractor reports that at this time, there is 1 pallet of batteries that fell off of a metal load rack apparently due to a load shift. The contractor advised that there were 2 batteries that were originally top loaded even though there are labels on the batteries indicating not to top load. The remaining batteries were re-loaded accordingly on the trailer floor.

column168: On October 3, 2014, R&L Carriers reported that (1) 55-gallon DM of Methyl Ethyl Ketone (MEK) had been punctured during loading operations as the result of a protruding nail on a skid. Approximately 15 gallons of product released onto the trailer floor. HazChem was dispatched out of Addison, IL to conduct clean-up operations. The damaged drum was over-packed into (1) 85-gallon steel over-pack. An additional drum of waste containing impacted absorbents was generated from this release. The over-pack was re-secured within the trailer and the waste was taken for pending disposal by HazChem. The trailer was completely cleaned; the site was restored to its previous condition.

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: On 10/12/2014, at 07:17, personnel in the CSXT Siebert yard in Mobile AL, discovered GATX 59033, a residue tank car of Liquefied Petroleum Gas, leaking from Vapor Line Valve. The car was isolated and the shipper Equistar Chemicals LP, Alabama EMA, City of Mobile Fire Department, NRC, and Chemtrec were notified.  CHEMTREC Report #2014-10-12-00009. SWS, a CSXT emergency response contractor, and the CSXT Hazardous Materials Manager were dispatched to the scene and found Vapor Line Valve a 1/4 turn open and the secondary securement plug 8 quarter turns loose. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Doug Rowland 832-386-5218. Contractor personnel closed the valve and tightened the secondary securement plug. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 is not required    Cause Code:136  NARRI:5(4+5+0) x (2+0) = 90

column168: During a routine walk through inspection at the Clean Harbors Environmental Services Inc. in-transit storage facility at Kent, WA a leaking drum was discovered. The drum was discovered to have a pin hole leak at the side wall resulting in a release of material. Facility management was notified and an in house crew responded. The response crew donned the proper PPE, over-packed the damaged drum and clean up debris into a suitable salvage drum, and secured the drum for continued transportation to the intended disposal facility. The Washington Emergency Management Division was notified. WEMD incident # 14-3943.
column169: At the time the driver accepted the container for transportation no evidence of leaking was observed. The shipper was advised of the incident and was requested to inspect all drums in current inventory for any containers with suspect integrity. The driver was re-instructed to perform a thorough inspection of all containers prior to accepting them for transportation and to reject or over pack any containers with suspect integrity into suitable salvage drums.

column168: When I, John Vergis, was inspecting our Brewster, Ohio yard I found PROX 43900 had a wetness on the sides at about 1600 hrs. I closed the sample valve by turning almost one complete turn and then the leak stopped.  I then tightened the valve plug. Old seal on Breadbox Lid was 458801 and the I installed a new seal of JJ Keller 00249477.  Repaired at 1620 hrs.

column168: At 0355 ET hours, Penny Foley of R&L Carriers contacted ERTS regarding the release of approximately 5 (five) gallons of a UN1789 HYDROCHLORIC ACID to the rear of a trailer and concrete dock area at the Woodinville WA terminal. At the time of this report, no drains, soils or waterways were reported as being impacted. ERTS will make the required regulatory reporting. The caller stated that during loading operations, a tow motor operator punctured the pail resulting in the release. A vapor cloud appeared and terminal personnel closed the trailer door and cleared the immediate area. ERTS has requested copies of the BOL & MSDS. ERTS has dispatched a network contractor with an approximate ETA of 2.5 hours. , only (1) 5-gallon pail has been noticed to be punctured and released its entire contents to the trailer floor. The contractor will sweep up the kitty litter that was already applied, and neutralize the impacted area prior to containerizing for pending disposal.

column168: The initial response was carried out by Environmental Restoration, L.L.C. Upon arrival, ER personnel discovered that the material was releasing from a 330 gallon tote that was located in the back of the trailer. The released material impacted the trailer surface as well as two (2) 55-gallon drums and wood pallets that were in the back of the trailer. The released material was being containerized into a 55-gallon drum to prevent the material from impacting the soil surface. ER personnel donned level B personnel protective equipment and rotated a 2 man in, 2 man out rotation to remediate the release. All cargo was removed from the trailer in order to conduct remedial actions. The remaining ammonium hydroxide that was in the 330 gallon tote was transferred into a secondary tote. All impacted cargo was removed for transport and disposal by ER personnel.  Two (2) 55-gallon drums and one (1) cubic yard of waste material was generated. Crew members then deployed speedy dry to absorb any free standing material and then allowed the trailer to air out so that any remaining ammonium hydroxide inside the trailer could evaporate.     Once the trailer was cleared to leave the site by the Massachusetts DOT and EPA, all non-impacted cargo, including the remaining ammonium hydroxide, was then loaded back into the trailer for transport and delivery. Mr. Bill Mitchel, with Clean Soils Environmental, Ltd was the Licensed State Professional contact for this job. The Massachusetts state report number for this incident is 4-25342.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Valve Open
column168: A BNSF train crew inspecting their train in the railyard reported entrained tank car UTLX 210687 dripping commodity from its bottom outlet valve (BOV) area. A BNSF mechanical responder immediately inspected UTLX 210687 and reported the BOV's operating handle was not properly pinned at its closed position. The applied pinning mechanism prevented the BOV operating handle to me moved to its closed position. The pinning mechanism was removed so the BOV operating handle could be moved to its full closed position. Once the BOV operating handle was correctly repositioned, the pinning mechanism was re-applied. The bottom outlet valve's closure cap (BOC) was found 3 full turns from a tool tight condition. The responder tool tightened the BOC and the very slow commodity drip ended. Afterwards, the responder removed the BOC to drain any captured commodity from the inside of the closure cap and inspect the condition of the BOC gasket. The BOC gasket was deemed serviceable and the BOC was re-applied and properly tool tightened. All spillage evaporated.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column42: NITRIC ACID OTHER THAN RED FUMING, WITH AT LEAST 65 PERCENT, BUT NOT MORE THAN 70 PERCENT NITRIC ACID
column168: As the operator was unloading of the rail car, The unloading pressure on the car increased, as the pressure increased he noticed that there was a small leak of 65% nitric acid at the valve attached to the rail car. The unloading operation was immediately stopped and the safety and environmental departments were immediately notified. The acid that leaked onto the ground was neutralized with soda ash. The car was immediately tagged out of service. TheDOT inspector came on-site the next morning to inspect the rail car. The inspector gave our operators the approval to tighten up the bolts and finish unloading the rail car. The remaining material in the rail car was safely unloaded. The rail car has been tagged out of service.
column169: We are looking at improving our unloading procedure to include a more thorough inspection of rail cars before theyare unloaded.

column168: PACKAGE WAS SITTING ON GRATING TO BE LOADED INTO CAR. EMPLOYEE PICKED UP PACKAGE, WALKED THREE STEPS TO ROLLERS AND REALIZED PACKAGE WAS WET. EMPLOYEE IMMEDIATELY SET PKG ON ROLLERS AND NOTICED HANDS TINGLING AND BURNING. EMPLOYEE TOLD SUPERVISOR. SUPERVISOR CLEARED AREA AND TOOK EMPLOYEE TO WASH HANDS SUPERVISOR BROUGHT EMPLOYEE TO SAFETY. RMP MADE EMPLOYEE FLUSH HAND WITH WATER FOR 15 MINUTES. RMP SENT SUPERVISOR TO GET RESPONDER FOR LEAKING PACKAGE. RESPONDER WEARING FULL PPE AND USING DECISION TREE, RESPONDED AND PICKED UP PACKAGE. RMP LOOKED UP SDS AND LOOKED AT PKG. RMP CHECKED ON EMPLOYEE RESPONDER FOLLOWED WASTE DISPOSAL AND GREEN BAGGED PACKAGE CONTENTS AND WET CARTON.
column169: EMPLOYEES BE MORE AWARE OF ORIENTATION ARROWS. TAKE EXTRA PRECAUTION WITH HAZMATS TO LOOK UNDER AND AROUND FOR SIGNS OF LEAK.

column168: Intermodal container MOAU 60912 (an import shipment from Japan) was reported leaking a black paint substance at the intermodal facility. MOAU 60912 was isolated at the facility's containment area. Contract responders inspecting the lading within MOAU 60912 reported finding one rectangular steel jerrican loaded on a pallet's bottom layer at the nose of the container that was dented and had leaked. The bottom corner of the jerrican cracked at the dented area allowing commodity to escape. Responders cleaned the paint spillage on the inside and outside of MOAU 60912. Afterwards, the lading removed from MOAU 60912 was returned properly blocked and braced. The damaged jerrican was wrapped in plastic and earmarked for appropriate disposal.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: During a routine Pre-trip inspection of a van trailer, a Clean Harbors driver observed a small amount of material leaking from the front portion of the trailer.  The van trailer was immediately staged in secondary containment. Clean Harbors F/S responded and found that a flex bin was leaking due to another flex bin that was staged on top causing the lower flex bin to be crushed somewhat.  The response team cleaned the material that leaked from the van.  They removed the upper flex bin and repackaged the contents of the lower flex bin into another flex bin and cleaned up any residue that was still inside the van.  The absorbent material and damaged flex bim were placed into a proper DOT container for disposal and relased for transportation to the intended disposal facility.
column169: Clean harbors contacted the loading facility regarding the situation and reminded them on proper loading procedures.

column168: Dispatch should monitor the online tank gauge before dispatching new loads to this location due to tank monitors not being visible for the driver when he arrives at the drop location. column169: Dispatchers got complacent due to them not thinking that this tank would ever overfill because of its extremely large size. They now know (should have in the first place) that checking the online gauges before delivery will not be overlooked.

column168: During a routine yard check at the ten day storage yard of the intended waste disposal facility, a small amount of liquid was found to be running out the back of the trailer.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and entered the trailer.  The trailer floor had liquid puddled on it which had come from a drum that was leaking from the bottom.  The drum was overpacked into a salvage container and the floor was cleaned with a suitable absorbant material.  The cleanup material along with a shovelful of dirt from the ground was also placed into the salvage drum.  The trailer was then taken into the intended disposal facility and unloaded without further incident.
column169: The drum had deteriorated on the bottom and sprung a leak.  The drum showed no signs of leaking when picked up and the trailer was not leaking when accepted into the ten day yard.  The origin location was notifed so that they can notify the shipper of the incident.

SWS was dispatched out of Atlanta, GA to overpack the drums that were found to have unsecured caps. column168: On October 6, 2014, Baker Hughes experienced a tote failure after (1) 330-gallon tote was dropped during loading operations from a fork-lift. The tote bottom consequently gave way when it fell from the fork lift and released approximately 120 gallons of UN1908 Sodium Chlorite 25% to the dirt/gravel lot, impacting an area measuring approximately 50'x60'. No drains or waterways were impacted. ERS of Oklahoma was dispatched to clean the released material on the lot. On-site Water Management personnel conducted a transfer of the remaining material into a new tote. All contaminated soils were collected and taken for disposal. The site was restored to its previous condition.

column168: Our tractor trailer was transporting several drums of waste Isopropyl Alcohol eastbound on I40 in Gallup NM. As our vehicle entered the scales it was discovered that a liquid was dripping out of the trailer. After being directed to pull into a segregation area an inspection, it was revealed that a drum had fallen over in the back of the trailer.  As the drum fell, it struck a load secure bar and which punctured a small hole in the side of the drum. The small puncture hole allowed the product to leak and it was estimated that 15 gallons were lost. Evirotech, a private environmental response company, responded and repacked the drum. The alcohol evaporated/dissipated prior to their arrival.
column169: We have begun to purchase new load straps to replace metal Loadbars.  We have instructed our employees to more diligent on cargo inspections as well as the frequencies

column168: A Clean Harbors Environmental Services Inc. truck was at a shipper's location in the process of loading multiple waste streams of drummed waste. During the loading process two drums that were picked up at a previous client’s location were observed to have minor leaks at the bottom weld/seam. The leaks appeared to be caused by corrosion of the drum material being caused by the waste the drum contained. Clean Harbors’ personnel donned the proper PPE and placed the leaking drums into properly rated salvage drums. The waste continued on to the designated disposal facility with no further issues. The release was reported to the Nebraska Department of Environmental Quality, report number 101014-ml-1930.
column169: At the time the driver accepted the drums for transportation no evidence of leaking was observed. The driver, however, was re-instructed to conduct a thorough inspection of each container before acceptance and if any evidence of a reduction in structural integrity is found to take appropriate action to either place the container into a suitable salvage drum, re containerize, or reject before transportation is initiated. In addition, the shipper was advised of the incident and instructed to verify that the waste being offered for transportation is placed in a compatible and DOT shippable container for all future shipments.

column25: Valero Marketing + Supply Co. by Intercontinental Terminals Co.
column168: Tank car GATX 18837 was reported emanating commodity from its manway closure while in the railyard. GATX 18837 was cordoned-off awaiting inspection from contract responders. Responders reported finding GATX 18837's manway gasket missing. A new Viton manway gasket was applied and the manway closure was properly re-secured.  All other valves and fittings were inspected and found secure. Intact shipper seals numbered 424018 and 424019 were replaced by seals numbered 7139997 and 7139996 respectively.  All spillage evaporated.  Response was concluded by 1630 hrs. CDT, 10/14/2014.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column25: Hanjin Shipping Company Ltd.by AgroChem Inc. (Farm + Dairy Products)
column42: FORMALDEHYDE SOLUTIONS, WITH NOT LESS THAN 25 PERCENT FORMALDEHYDE
column168: Intermodal container HJCU 157105 was reported dripping an unknown liquid substance onto the pavement while it was parked in the intermodal facility's lot. HJCU 157105 was carefully moved to the containment area for lading inspection and spill remediation. Contract responders inspecting the lading within HJCU 157105 reported finding one steel caged 275 gallon poly tote/IBC dripping commodity from its bottom fitted outlet valve. Responders could not stop the dripping from this valve and its contents was transferred to another suitable IBC without further incident. It appeared that the gasket between the outlet valve and the poly tote was not sealing. Spillage inside and the underside of HJCU 157105 was cleaned.  The ground spillage (estimated at one gallon) was cleaned from the pavement at the intermodal parking lot. All other lading removed was returned inside HJCU 157105 properly blocked and braced for further transportation. Spent cleaning materials and the empty tote were earmarked for appropriate disposal.
column169: No additional comments.
column172: Composite, with a rigid plastic inner receptacle for liquids and a steel outer packaging

column25: ASTRA Oil Company, LLC / Crestwood Logistics, LLC
column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: (A)On October 28th, 2014 at 08:48 hours, personnel in the CSXT Frontier Yard discovered NATX 301538, a loaded UN 1267, Petroleum Crude Oil tank car to have wetness down the side of the tank car coming from around the manway. The car was isolated and the Shipper, ASTRA Oil Company, LLC, was notified via CHEMTREC, report 2014-10-28-00060. A CSX Emergency Response contractor, EP+S of Vermont the Buffalo branch was dispatched to the scene, upon inspection it was determined that the release was from around manway cover swing bolt #1, all other swings were tool tight, the manway was opened, the gasket was inspected and found no exceptions, but the gasket was wet and showing oily residue, therefore it would be a misaligned manway cover. The nozzle was wipe down and the cover was re-secured and tool tightened. Mr. John Rolniak, with Bridger Trading Co. LLC., Cell 318-272-6828 was notified of the situation found and the corrective action taken. NATX 301538 was released for transport. This incident did NOT require a special move. column168: Truck owner by Davidson Surface Air was traveling on I-70 EB at MM 19.  Another tractor trailer changed lanes in front of the Davidson truck causing the driver to slam on his brakes.  The load shifted due to the sudden deceleration causing one of the totes of Phosphoric Acid to be punctured and leak.     Approximately 150-200 gallons of the product leaked into the trailer and onto the ground under the trailer.  The local fire department and hazmat unit were called to the scene.  The local fire department set up containment pools to catch the leaking material.      Summit Environmental came to the scene and completed the remediation on site.

column168: On October 14, 2014, at 19:48 hours, Mechanical Foreman at the CSXT Willard Yard, Willard, Ohio reported that puffs of smoke were visible coming from the top of SHPX 203441, a residue tank car of UN1789, hydrochloric acid. The tank car was removed from the outbound train and isolated. The shipper, AK Steel, was notified via Chemtrec, report #2014-1014-00257 . Eagle Railcar, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the Willard Yard. Eagle Railcar found that the PRV was releasing vapor and would need to be further inspected. The shipper representative, Larry, 513-594-3541 was notified of the situation found. The frangible disk was found to have separated and delaminated. The disk was replaced temporarily until Olin Corp. could supply a new frangible disk, gasket and centering device.  This incident did require a special move. column168: While on the loading dock at the San Jose TSDF Plant, outgoing drums were being transferred from the drum storage area to a van trailer for outbound shipping to the ultimate disposal facility.  the first forklift driver was heading to the loading dock ramp saw that it was clear and proceeded to make the 180 degree turn so as to place the double-stack pallet of drum down next to the ramp.  During this maneuver, a second forklift driver who had been unloading in a trailer at the dock exited the trailer and started to back down the ramp.  This driver, when at the base of the ramp, saw the approaching first forklift, sounded his horn and stopped.  The first driver (still double-stacked)heard the horn at some point and hit the brakes.  He had not completed setting the pallet down when he made contact with the second forklift.  The pallet broke and the drum fell the short distance to the ground resulting in the spill.  The drum was overpacked, the spilled material cleaned up and disposed of appropriately.
column169: The incident was investigated and found the first driver should have waited until the ramp was clear.  The driver will retake forklift driving and safety training.  Additional mirrors will be installed on the ramp.

column168: Tank car GATX 56455 in the railyard was reported with a commodity stain that emanated from its manway area. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder inspected GATX 56455 and reported finding 5 of 6 manway securement eyebolts less than tool tight and one eyebolt not applied/hanging. The responder properly secured all six eyebolts to a tool tight condition. Afterwards, contract responders tasked to clean GATX 56455 applied 'micro-blaze' onto the commodity spillage, water rinsed and wiped down GATX 56455. A small amount of commodity drippage from GATX 56455's side shell onto a cross-tie and surrounding ballast was also remediated. Cleaning was completed by 1630 hrs. CDT, 10/14/2014.    Per conversation with a shipper representative, prior to the GATX 56455's arrival on the BNSF at Houston, it was held on the PTRA (Anderson Railyard) in Houston for commodity sampling/testing. Afterwards, GATX 56455 was rerouted to another consignee. Apparently, the testing service provider (AmSpec) failed to properly secure the manway closure after the commodity sampling was completed on the PTRA.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: Incident Number 2014101100055  At 0905 hours Air Liquide received a call from Chemtrec about a railroad tank car which was venting in the railroad yard at Kansas City Southern (KCS) in Shreveport LA.  A hazardous material specialist for KCS, Steve McNeilly, had called Chemtrec asking for help.  The venting railcar, IAPX 1029, was carrying Argon with a destination of Rockford IL; the shipper was Air Liquide in Nederland, TX.      Air Liquide Fleet Safety Specialist, Victor Crystal, called Mike Konnovitch in Kansas City Southern Railroad, Shreveport and discussed the incident with him.   The following information was shared:  1.  The railroad tank car was operating within design pressure.  2.  It is normal for the road safety to vent occasionally to control pressure fluctuations.  Victor thought the difference in the temperature between Bayport and Shreveport may have caused a pressure increase quicker than the road safety could handle.  The Pressure Safety Valve (PSV) may have briefly opened to release excess pressure.  3.  Mr. Konnovitch told Victor the PSV had stopped venting without intervention and the road safety was only slowly venting as designed.  Kansas City Southern (KCS) did not require any spill clean-up activities and allowed the car to proceed to its destination.  KCS did break the shipping seals and replaced them.
column169: Railroad tank car IAPX 1029 is currently under evaluation.  The tank car will be inspected, tested and monitored with any findings that may have contributed to this incident immediately addressed to prevent re-occurrence.

column168: CN Engineering crew reported a strong odor coming from tank car CBTX 728665 (L / Petroleum Crude Oil, UN1267, PGII) as it traveled through the Stevens Point Yard, Stevens Point, WI. All appropriate departments notified and tank car isolated. CN's response team responded noting one of eight manway bolts less than tool tight allowing product and vapor to be released. The shipper's security seal was intact on arrival. Manway gasket replaced and swing bolts tightened securing the manway. Product on exterior was removed. Car was released to Transportation for movement to destination

column168: On October 31, 2014, an R&L Carriers shipment of hazardous material experienced a spill. Approximately 10 gallons of Sodium Hydroxide (UN3266 Corrosive liquid) released from (1) 15-gallon poly drum as the result of inadequate blocking and bracing which led to a puncture. The release occurred along I-20 EB from Longview, TX to Shreveport, LA. The release along the highway was too small to be visible or cleaned as it occurred over an extended period. The trailer floor and asphalt area found to be impacted in Shreveport were completely cleaned and all contaminated material was taken for disposal by USES out of Shreveport, LA. The site was restored to its previous condition.

column168: The Basin Western truck and trailer overturned onto left side while making the transition from Hwy 6 to Hwy 13 near Rifle, Colorado. The overturned tank then slid across a traffic sign of which the base punctured left side of cargo tank resulting in an 8" hole and release of cargo. The cargo flowed across HWY 13 lanes and into collection basins for approximately 20 minutes. Absorbent socks and plastic covering were immediately employed in an effort to contain cargo until appropriate cleanup efforts could begin.
column169: The accident investigation determined that driver was not on approved route and traveling at an unacceptable rate of speed for given area when accident occurred. As a result Basin Western Inc. will be working with Colorado State Patrol to provide awareness training regarding approved HazMat routes. In addition Basin Western Inc. will create safeguards within the electronic logging devices to help monitor and identify any future violation of approved routes/speed in the affected area.

FSTI driver leaves Point Comfort with a load of 50% caustic in route for a delivery in Austin, TX.    FSTI driver is driving northbound on USHWY 183 approaching the town of Lockhart when a flat bed trailer pulls out in front of him.  The driver brakes hard to avoid the collision. As the driver try's to regains speed. Traffic behind him starts to backup and cars begin to pass him on his left hand side.  As he is scanning his mirrors the driver notices that his back right trailer axle is too close to the edge.  By the time the driver is able to react the trailer walks off the side of the road in the ditch.  The truck and trailer quickly roll into the ditch because of the slope. The driver tries to steer back onto the road but the weight  and forces involved with the sloshing liquid roll both the truck and trailer over .  The equipment takes 2 rolls and stops on its side with the drivers door facing the ground.    Lockhart Fire Dept and EMS respond to the accident and the diver is transported to Seton Edgar B. Davis Hospital in Luiling, TX.  The driver is found with no major injuries and is released from the hospital in a few hours.    Emergency Responders notify FSTI of the incident.  FSTI Ownership and Management briefed of situation and FSTI sets in motion emergency response with Emergency Response Contractor to assess the situation.  It was noted upon arrival that neither truck or trailer were going to be safely moved.  Another empty FSTI trailer was brought into the incident area and a 3rd party emergency response crew performs the transfer and ensures that everything is performed safely and correctly.     Details of the HM release-  The washout caps on the top of the tanker trailer were leaking residual caustic out the top of the trailer wash out caps at a few drips a minute. Emergency personal tighten caps and drips stop. Also during the rollover a small amount of diesel had leaked out of the diesel tank via the cap. After accident this leaked had stopped by itself after the truck settles. There was less than a pint of each for each of these materials that had spilled.    As a precaution and due to the uncertainty of the hazmat material Emergency crews onsite shut the down road and evacuated businesses that were close until our emergency response crews could assess the situation.  Once they felt comfortable all were opened back up.
column169: Retraining of the Driver (completed 10.31.14- details below)    Classroom Training with 3rd Party Driving School  FSTI DRIVER involved went through a 5 day classroom discussion course that was tailored to the incident  • Post-accident discussions on what went wrong in his accident  • What he could have done to correct it  • What he can do to avoid it in the future  • Reviewed the CDL driver handbook (specifically 14-2)  • Watched a video on different rollover scenarios  • Watched a video and discussed rollover prevention techniques  • Reviewed the SNITCH system (driving technique)  • Tanker specific video and discussion    Over The Road Driver Training 3rd Party  He spent approximately 3 hours each day under teacher supervision   • performed multiple driving skills in a truck  • observing other students   • pre/post inspection activity     Received a Road Test from 3rd Party  The last day of the class he did a road test with one of the teachers.  He passed this test     Refresher FSTI offload procedures   As an extra precaution we had him do a final ride along with one of our senior drivers.  We wanted to make sure that he was current with all of our checklists and equipment.  He also passed this test.    New FSTI Driver Training Requirements  An abbreviated form of this program is being blended into our new hire training process.   After initial training new hires will report to this school for a 3 day training session to ensure that they have proper rollover prevention & driver training.  This was already being done at FSTI but we wanted to take our training program to the next level to ensure that these type of accidents never happen again.     Futhermore, this training program will now also be a requirement for any drivers that are involved in a wreck with the company to ensure that we are providing the proper training and sign off to return to work.       Other Precautions rolled out to the fleet immediately after incident-    Driver rollover awareness and lessons learned call – All FSTI Drivers  BH 10/3/14(completed) Items review below    Review of the rollover incident  Importance of reporting unsafe road conditions  Duty and empowerment for each driver to stop the job when unsafe conditions exist  Rollover review and safety    Create change meet and greet.  Onsite Visits to each site were conducted to discuss rollovers and safety with Drivers immediately after wreck– Brian (FSTI CEO) 10/8 (completed)

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  The tanker split in the middle due to structural damage.  Several hundred gallons of free product were released.  Local Fire Department, Police Department and Department of Transportation responded to assess the site.  Local DOT deployed sand to contain the free liquid.  Environmental Product & Services, Inc. of Vermont (EPS) of Lancaster, New York was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  EPS arrived and prepared to transfer the remaining product.  EPS was unable to transfer the product because the product had cooled off.  It was decided to perform a controlled release of the product.  The ditch line was bermed and the product was released.  The free liquid was mixed with sand to turn into a solid.  EPS collected the material and placed into roll-off boxes for disposal.  No injuries or exposures were reported.
column169: Since the release was accidental, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  However, Connell Transport Ltd. will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: On 10/16/14 at approx. 0130, company transport driver was traveling southbound on US 285 near MM 320 when he  observed a fire originating at the rear axle, drivers side of the trailer. Driver pulled off roadway on the west improved  shoulder of US 285 upright facing south. The fire quickly grew out of control so the driver evacuated the area and  called for emergency services. The fire department responded to the scene and extinguished the fire, but not before  the cargo tanks rear compartment was severely damaged. The cargo tank contained only residue at the time of  incident, so no product was lost.
column169: Investigation concluded that the driver may have driven on an underinflated tire which subsequently caught on fire.  Enhance driver training on the importance of checking tire pressure each change of duty status.

column168: THE LOADER AT DOOR 170 WAS REMOVING PACKAGES FROM AN IRREG TRAIN WHEN SHE SAW A WET SPOT UNDER A HAZMAT PACKAGE.  SHE IMMEDIATELY TOLD THE NEAREST SUPERVISOR, CODY.  CODY NOTIFIED THE DESIGNATED RESPONSDER OF THE LEAKING HAZMAT PACKAGE WHEN I ARRIVED TO THE AREA.  I UTILIZED THE DECISION TREE/RESPONSE SHEETS. BECAUSE THE PACKAGE WAS CORROSIVE, I ALTERED MY PPE TO INCLUDE THE SILVER SHIELD INNER LINERS. AFTER TESTING THE PH OF THE LIQUID, I CONTAINERIZED THE LEAKING DRUM TO A LINED SPILL TRAY.  THEMN I APPLIED SODIUM BICARBONATE TO THE LIQUID TO NEUTRALIZE IT.  I PERIODICALLY RETEST THE PH UNTIL THE TAPE GAVE A NEUTRAL READING BETWEEN 6-9.  THEN I USED CLAY BASED ABSORBANT TO SOLIDIFY ANY REMAINING LIQUID.  I SWEPT UP ALL THE CONTAMINATED MATERIALS & ADDED THEM TO THE SPILL TRAY. I THEN TOOK THE PACKAGE TO THE DMP AREA FOR PROCESSEING.  I COULD SEE THAT THERE WAS A PUNCTURE HOLE IN THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM.

YOST AGREED TO SEND A SUBCONTRACTOR TO THE SITE WITH TOOLS AND PPE NECESSARY TO EITHER TIGHTEN THE FITTING OR TO REPLACE THE GASKETS IN THE CAMLOCKS.
column169: THE TANKER WAS CLEANED AND INSPECTED JUST PRIOR TO PICKING UP THIS LOAD. THE CLEANING COMPANY FAILED TO TIGHTEN ALL FITTINGS UPON COMPLETION OF THEIR SEVICES. SMITH SYSTEMS WILL PROVIDE NOTICE TO THE CLEANING COMPANY OF THE FAILURE AND ENSURE THEY COMPLETELY INSPECT ALL FITTING PRIOR TO RELEASING THE TANKER FOR SERVICE.

column168: Driver loaded Ethanol at the Patriot Annanwan IL facility at approximately 6:45 am on October 13, 2014. He left the facility and headed East Bound on I-80. At approximately 7:15 am at mile marker 38 he left the roadway for unknown reasons and both tractor/trailer units overturned into the ditch off the right shoulder. The driver was ejected from the tractor. The trailer had a minor leak as a result of the rollover. Emergency personnel were notified immediately and arrived on scene shortly thereafter. Emergency response team placed hazmat pads on the ground under the leak to minimize the spill. The load of ethanol was then transferred to another cargo tank trailer and delivered to the original destination. Upon receipt of the scale tickets and BOL's, there was no difference in the gallons loaded to the gallons actually delivered.
column169: Because it is unknown at this time as to the reason why the driver left the roadway and we can only speculate; we will be implementing additional safety training, including reinforcing to our drivers the importance wearing their seatbelts and minimizing distractions while driving, actions to take if the tractor/trailer leaves the roadway and recovering.

column168: UPS EMPLOYEE AT THE SALT LAKE CITY HUB NOTICED SMOKE COMING FROM A PACKAGE SHORTLY AFTER IT WAS UNLOADED FROM THE PICK-UP VEHICLE, JUST A FEW HOURS FROM THE TIME OF PICK-UP. THE PACKAGE WAS REMOVED FROM THE SORTING OPERATION. INVESTIGATION SHOWED THE CONTENTS WERE TWO LITHIUM BATTERIES CONTAINED IN AN UNMARKED FIBERBOARD BOX.  ON THE BASIS OF AN ACCOMPANYING INVOICE, UPS BELIEVES THE BATTERIES EACH HAD A CAPACITY OF 455 WH AND WERE BEING RETURNED TO THE CONSIGNEE FOLLOWING A RECENT PURCHASE. THE BATTERIES HAD SOMEHOW OVERHEATED, SCORCHING THE INSIDE OF THE BOX THAT CONTAINED THEM. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR FACILITY DAMAGE. CLOSE EXAMINATION OF THE PACKAGING REVEALED THAT AN OPAQUE, WHITE TAPE HAD BEEN APPLIED OVER PREVIOUSLY USED UPS HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SHIPPING PAPERS FOR A SHIPMENT ON UN3480.  THE TAPE ALSO COVERED THE ASSOCIATED HAZARD MARKINGS AND CLASS 9 LABEL.

column168: Tank car DBUX 301422 was reported leaking commodity that emanated from its manway closure while in the railyard. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder inspected DBUX 301422 and reported finding 4 of 6 manway securement eyebolt nuts loose with two of these only hand tight. The responder tool tightened these loose manway securement eyebolt nuts. Afterwards, DBUX 301422 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard in order to clean the commodity spillage from DBUX 301422.   In the morning of 10/21/2014, a response contractor arrived to clean the spillage from DBUX 301422 and re-inspect its manway closure securement. The contract responders opened the manway closure and reported that the manway gasket was missing. The commodity outage was observed as being sufficient. A new manway nozzle gasket was installed and the manway closure was properly re-secured. The spillage on DBUX 301422 was wiped and cleaned. Spent cleaning materials were collected inside a drum liner and placed into the facility's oil filter compactor at the diesel shop. Contractor response was concluded by 1145 hrs. MDT, 10/21/2014.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column62: Valve Open; Missing Component or Device
column168: BNSF was notified by local authorities of a fresh trail of oil along the tracks and right of way. The BNSF train dispatcher notified the train crew of the train that recently passed the location provided by the authorities. The BNSF train was stopped on main track for inspection and the train crew reported entrained tank car VMSX 280616 was leaking commodity from its top fitting area. VMSX 280616 was set-out from its train at a nearby side track. Contract responders inspecting VMSX 280616 reported finding the liquid valve in the open position and its closure plug not applied but sitting atop the valve port's threaded orifice. The liquid valve was closed and its closure plug was inserted and tool tightened.  Responders surveyed the right of way and applied 'micro-blaze' solution to ground areas observed with commodity spillage. VMSX 280616's outage was gauged to estimate quantity of possible commodity loss. The spillage on VMSX 280616 was cleaned on site. VMSX 280616 was returned to the shipper for additional detailed cleaning of any residual spillage.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: ON 10/20/2014 TRIAD TRANSPORT, INC ARRIVED AT GWINNETT CO. DEPT. OF WATER RESOURCES LANIER FILTER PLANT AT 2601 BUFORD DAM ROAD IN BUFROD, GEORGIA. THAT FACILITY HAD REQUESTED A VACUUM TANK TRANSPORT OF HAZARDOUS WASTE THROUGH EQ DETROIT, INC. AND TRIAD WAS NOTIFIED AND ACCEPTED THE LOAD. UPON ARRIVAL THEY LOADED 3,235 GALLONS OF WASTE FERRIC CHLORIDE SOLUTION (A CLASS 8 CORROSIVE) ON TRIAD'S STAINLESS STEEL VACUUM TANK TRAILER. THIS PRODUCT WAS NOT COMPATIBLE WITH THE STAINLESS STEEL TANK AND THEY SHOULD HAVE ORDERED A LINED STEEL TANK.    THIS CORROSIVE MATERIAL CAUSED THE TANK TO FAIL AND A LEAK BEGAN AND WAS DETECTED IN KENTUCKY ON INTERSTATE 75 NEAR EXIT 95. ON 10/21/2014 AT APPROXIMATELY 09:00HRS A KENTUCKY HIGHWAY PATROL UNIT STOPPED THE TRUCK BECAUSE HE WAS DRIPPING LIQUID. IT WAS AT FIRST THOUGHT BY THE DRIVER THAT THE PACKING AROUND THE LEVEL GAUGE ON THE SIDE OF THE TRAILER HAD FAILED AND CAUSED A LEAK. THE DRIVER PULLED A FRESH VACUUM ON THE TRAILER WHEN GOT OUT OF THE TRUCK AND SAW THE LEAK; WHICH APPEARED TO STOP THE LEAK FOR A TIME. AFTER LOOKING AT THE DRIVER'S MANIFEST AND PAPERWORK AND DETERMINING WHAT THE PRODUCT WAS, THE KENTUCKY HIGHWAY PATROL TOOK CHARGE OF THE SCENE. THIS WAS A VERY SMALL AND FAIRLY SLOW DRIP AND THE MADISON CO. KENTUCKY EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT CLOSED THE HIGHWAY. THEY IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED NRC (THIS WAS BEFORE TRIAD SAFETY DEPT. WAS NOTIFIED). NRC ASSIGNED NUMBER 1098879 TO THE INCIDENT. TRIAD WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT BY THE DRIVER AT APPROXIMATLEY 09:30. SAFETY DIRECTOR JOHN WATKINS CALLED THE NRC TO REPORT THE INCIDENT AND WAS TOLD IT HAD ALREADY BEEN REPORTED AND WAS GIVEN THE NUMBER.    WITHIN MINUTES OF THE INITIAL STOP BY KENTUCKY HIGHWAY PATROL; MADISON CO. EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT, THE MADISON CO. FIRE DEPT. AND KENTUCKY DEPT. OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION HAD RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.    IT WAS SOON DISCOVERED AT THE SCENE THAT THE TANK WAS BEING CORRODED BY THE MATERIAL AND THE A HOLE HAD DEVELOPED JUST ABOVE THE GAUGE. AT THE REQUEST OF THE KENTUCKY HIGHWAY PATROL ANOTHER TRIAD TANK WAS BROUGHT TO THE SCENE AND THE MATERIAL WAS TRANS-LOADED ON TO THE OTHER TANK. THIS OPERATION BEGAN AT APPROXIMATELY 13:00HRS. EQ WAS ALSO NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED WITH A RUBBER LINED TANK AS THE OTHER TRIAD TANK WAS ALSO A STAINLESS STEEL TANK. AFTER TRANS-LOADING THE TANK TRAILER WITH THE MATERIAL WAS MOVED TO A VACANT GRAVELED AREA NEAR EXIT 95 APPROXIMATELY TWO MILES AWAY. THE EQ TANK ARRIVED AT APPROXIMATELY 20:00HRS., AND THEN TRANS-LOADED THE PRODUCT AND PROCEEDED ON WITH THE LOAD.    THE HIGHWAY HAD ALREADY BEEN OPENED AND TRAFFIC WAS FLOWING AT APPROXIMATELY 15:00HRS. PECCO ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTING RESPONDED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL AND WAS DONE WITH THE HIGHWAY AND AT THE LOT WHERE TRANS-LOADING TOOK PLACE AT APPROXIMATELY 9:00 PM.
column169: AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT, ALL TRIAD CUSTOMERS ARE REQUIRED TO CHECK COMPATIBILITY OF THEIR PRODUCT WITH STAINLESS STEEL TANKS. A DISCLAIMER HAS BEEN ADDED TO ALL TANK DIVISION EMAILS AND RATE QUOTES ADVISING OF THIS. IN ADDITION TRIAD LOAD PLANNERS ALSO DOUBLE CHECK COMPATIBILITY AND ATTEMPT TO DETERMINE THE PRODUCT AND ITS COMPATIBILITY TO THE STAINLESS STEEL TANK AS WELL AS ANY RESIDUE LAST CONTAINED.

column172: Pallet, used only for battery reports when no other container given

column168: A FORKLIFT DRIVER WAS LOADING A DOUBLE-STACKED PALLET OF 8 DRUMS ONTO A TRUCK FOR AN OUTBOUND SHIPMENT. AS THE FORKLIFT DRIVER WAS APPROACHING THE LOADING DOCK, THE DRUMS AT THE TOP OF THE STACK FELL FROM THE LOAD ONTO THE INDOOR LOADING DOCK FLOOR. THE LIDS ON TWO OF THE DRUMS BECAME DAMAGED CAUSING THOSE DRUMS TO RELEASE A TOTAL OF 75 GALLONS OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL INTO THE BUILDING. OF THOSE 75 GALLONS, APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS FLOWED UNDER THE DOCK PLACE ONTO THE PAVED OUTDOOR PARKING LOT. THE RELEASE DID NOT AFFECT SOIL, SURFACE WATER OR STORM DRAINS. THE DURATION OF THE RELEASE WAS INSTANTANEOUS. THE DAMAGED DRUMS WERE IMMEDIATELY PLACED IN UPRIGHT POSITION, AND BERMS WERE PLACED AROUND THE LOADING DOCK DOORS AND DOCK PLATES TO STOP ANY ADDITIONAL MATERIAL FROM ESCAPING. THE AFFECTED PORTION OF THE BUILDING WAS EVACUATED FOR APPROXIMATELY 20 MINUTES UNTIL THE TYPE OF MATERIAL WAS CONFIRMED, AND IT WAS DETERMINED TO BE SAFE TO RETURN TO THE BUILDING. THE RELEASED MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED USING A COMBINATION OF VERMICULATE, CONTAINMENT PADS, AND CONTAINMENT SOCKS TO BUILD A BERM AROUND THE MATERIAL. ONCE CONTAINED, CLEANUP ACTIVITIES BEGAN. ADDITIONAL VERMICULITE WAS PLACED ON THE MATERIAL TO ABSORB EXCESS LIQUID. ALL LIQUIDS WERE ABSORBED AND ALL CLEANUP MATERIAL WAS PLACED INTO DRUMS FOR PROPER DISPOSAL. THE DAMAGED DRUMS WERE PLACED IN OVER-PACKS.  THE DRUMS INVOLVED IN THIS INCIDENT CONTAINED  UN3266 FREE LIQUIDS. THESE DRUMS WERE OPEN-HEAD PLASTIC DRUMS RATED AS 1H/Y130/S/12/USA/M4232, WHICH ARE NOT RATED FOR FREE LIQUIDS. THE INCORRECT PACKAGING OF THE MATERIAL CONTRIBUTED TO THE INCIDENT. IT WAS ALSO DETERMINED THAT ONE OF THE WOODEN PALLETS THE WAS USED FOR THE LOAD WAS DAMAGED/BROKEN, CAUSING THE LOAD TO BE UNSTABLE AND ALSO CONTRIBUTING TO THE CAUSE OF THE INCIDENT.    THIS MATERIAL WAS INTENDED TO SHIP ON MANIFEST NUMBER 010778758JJK, AS NOTED IN PART II, NUMBERS 12 AND 20. AS A RESULT OF THE SPILL, THE MATERIAL WAS NOT SHIPPED ON THE LOAD. THE REMAINING MATERIAL AND SPILL CLEANUP WASTE DRUMS SHIPPED ON 11/13/14 ON MANIFEST NUMBER 010778769JJK.    20. EPA MANIFEST NUMBER SHOULD READ 010778758JJK.  25. ADDITIONAL FAILURE CODES:
column169: PREVENTATIVE MEASURE TAKEN TO PREVENT RE-OCCURRENCE INCLUDE:  -IMPLEMENTING WEIGHT RESTRICTIONS ON DOUBLE-STACKED PALLETS  -ADDITIONAL INSPECTIONS OF PALLETS BEFORE USING/LOADING TO ENSURE ONLY PALLETS IN GOOD CONDITION ARE USED FOR TRANSPORTATION  -RE-TRAINING EMPLOYEES ON DOT PACKAGING REQUIREMENTS FOR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS3. WHAT FAILED: 109 HOW FAILED: 302 CAUSES OF FAILURE: 511

column25: High Sierra Crude Oil + Marketing  LLC by Rocky Mountain Transload Inc.
column168: Tank car TEIX 30000 was reported with commodity spillage on its side shell that emanated from its manway closure while in the railyard. A BNSF mechanical responder placed absorbent padding under TEIX 30000 to capture any drippage off its side shell. Contract responders reported the shipper seal at the manway closure numbered 03594 was intact. Responders opened the manway and determined the commodity outage was sufficient. The gasket installed in the manway cover gasket groove most likely was not providing a good seal. A new Salco nitrile manway nozzle gasket was installed and the manway closure was properly re-secured. All other valves and fittings were inspected and found secure. All spillage on TEIX 30000 was cleaned.    Per side qualification stencil: Tank Qualified 2006 Due 2016
column169: ENSURE SHIPPER'S PRE-TRIP INSPECTION PROCESS IS FULLY IMPLEMENTED AND VALIDATED AS IT RELATES TO THE TOTAL SECUREMENT AND MECHANICAL FITNESS OF ALL VALVES AND FITTINGS.

column62: Conveyer or Material Handling Equipment Mishap
column168: THE DRIVER WAS IN THE PROCESS OF MAKING THE DELIVERY. REGULAR GASOLINE WAS FLOWING INTO THE UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK. THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO REMOVE ANOTHER DELIVERY HOSE FROM THE TRAILER HOSE TRAY. THE COUPLER ON THE FAR END OF THE HOSE THAT HE REMOVED FELL DOWN UPON THE ACTIVE DELIVERY HOSE CONNECTION AT THE DISCHARGE VALVE. AN EAR OPENED ON THE CONNECTION AND THE HOSE POPPED OFF CAUSING THE SPILL. THE DRIVER SHUT OFF THE VALVE AND ATTEMPTED TO CONTAIN THE SPILL WITH MATERIALS FROM THE SPILL KIT.  THE CAANAN VFD HAPPENED TO BE SITUATED ON THE SAME LOT AS THE GAS STATION AND RESPONDED TO CLEAN UP THE STANDING PRODUCT.  THE INCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO THE ACE SPILL REPSONSE CENTER WHO MADE THE NECESSARY NOTIFICATIONS TO THE VARIOUS REGULATORY AGENCIES AND SCHEDULED CLEAN HARBORS TO RESPOND AND CLEAN UP THE CONTAINMENT SOIL.  THE WV DEP WAS NOTIFIED BY A CONCERNED CITIZEN AND RESPONDED TO THE SCENE JUST AFTER THE INCIDENT OCCURED. WV DEP COORDINATED WITH THE DRIVER AS WELL AS WITH CLEAN HARBORS TO FACILITATE THE CLEAN UP. WITHIN A COUPLE OF DAYS THE SITE WAS EXCAVATED AND THE CONTAMINATED SOIL REPLACED.
column169: FOLLOWING THE INCIDENT, DURING SAFETY MEETINGS CONDUCTED WITH DRIVERS THROUGHOUT THE FLEET THE INCIDENT WAS DESCRIBED. THE POLICY THAT "NO OTHER ACTIVITY (SUCH AS HANDLING HOSES OR FITTING) IS TO BE UNDERTAKEN WHILE PRODUCT TRANSFER IS IN PROGRESS" WAS RE-ITERATED.  ALL DRIVERS MUST ONLY ATTEND THE DELIVERY; NOT ONLY DOES HANDLING EQUIPMENT DURING PRODUCT TRANSFER TAKE FOCUS OFF OF ATTENDANCE OF THE PRODUCT TRANSFER, IT ALSO POSES A TRIP AND FALL RISK WHILE WORKING AROUND ACTIVE EQUIPMENT AREAS.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: 15 gallon non-bulk container containing Hypochlorite solutions was found leaking in delivery trailer during Roadside Inspection at rest area.    The driver turned the container upside down to stop the leak as it was determined that the leak was from the bottom of the container. A spill response company was contacted and they dispatched out a crew to clean the trailer and pavement around the trailer where product had leaked.    It appeared that the container had developed a groove in the bottom from the pallet it was resting on when it shifted in transit; this created a hole allowing the product to develop a slow leak out of the bottom.
column169: The packaging was new and manufactured in 2013.  It was found that two pallets of product were secured to the trailer using one load strap.  In the future, pallets of liquid containers are to be individually strapped to prevent any future movement of containers on pallets which is what caused the hole to develop.    Loading personnel and drivers were informed of the incident and trained on this procedure at the next scheduled training session which was November 8, 2014.

column168: The trucking company loaded a heavy package and awkward package onto of the DGR drums.  When attempting to offload the shipments from the truck one of the DGR drums was damaged, causing a small amount (0.25L ) OF SPILLAGE.   Hazardous material response company stored in recovery drum. column168: At 1248 EST CSR Safety/Maintenance with Con-way Freight contacted ERTS, an emergency response contractor coordinator, to mitigate a hazardous UN2922 Hydrofluoric acid release (haz class 8, PG II, PRO# 661335286). Approximately 50 gallons and counting has reportedly been released from (1) 330-gallon tote as the result of improper blocking and bracing/load shift when the driver hit a pot hole at a customer's location.   The acid was released onto the dirt lot below and the trailer floor; no drains or waterways were impacted. The RQ for Hydrofluoric acid is 100 lbs. Due to the potential for this RQ to be exceeded, the following regulatory notifications were made:  NRC was contacted; P.O. Ennis issued RTN# 1097175 SERC was contacted; Scott issued RTN# 201410020028 LEPC was contacted via 911 by the driver, Jeff McGee; no RTN# available PA DEP Southwest was contacted; A voicemail was left with the duty officer for the region CHEMTREC was contacted; Ken Lavezzo issued RTN# 2014100200137. MSDS was requested for this material and supplied by Honeywell, the HM shipper.   Contractor arrived and unloaded the trailer with a forklift.  The remaining material in the tote was transferred from the tote into salvage drums and put back on the trailer.  The dirt lot has been neutralized and all solidified waste has been containerized in 55-gallon drums. A total of (6) 55-gallon poly drums of usable product was able to be salvaged from the tote. Additionally, (2) 55-gallon drums of non-hazardous waste had been generated. Once the trailer has been cleaned, all salvaged product and non-haz waste will be re-secured within the trailer to be shipped back to the XPB terminal. The pallet that was impacted was also neutralized.  The total quantity of acid (.5% concentration) released from the tote as a result of the load shift was determined to be ~30 gallons. The RQ was confirmed not to have been exceeded.

column168: DESCRIPTION OF INCIDENT: ON SATURDAY OCTOBER 18, 2014 TRANSPORT DRIVER PHIL JAMES LOADED T-21 AT THE ARNEGARD BULK FACILITY AND WAS DISPATCHED TO FUEL KODIAK UNIT 122. AROUND 6:45PM WHILE DRIVING ON I-85 NEAR MILE MARKER 157 THE DRIVELINE ON THE T-21 PUP TRAILER SHEERED OFF PUNCTURING THE TANK CAUSING RED DIESEL FUEL TO SPILL OUT OF THE TANK. PHIL JAMES WAS UNDER THE IMPRESSION THAT HE HAD BLOWN A TIRE AND STARTED TO PULL OVER IMMEDIATELY, DUE TO THE WEIGHT OF THE TRUCK AND THE MOMENTUM IT TOOK .75 MILES FOR THE TRUCK TO COME TO A COMPLETE STOP. DURING THIS TIME 3,300 GALLONS OF FUEL SPILLED ONTO THE SIDE OF THE HIGHWAY AND THE SOIL ON THE SIDE OF THE ROAD. NO WATERWAYS WERE IN CLOSE PROXIMITY OF THE SPILL, SO NO WATERWAYS WERE AFFECTED BY THE RELEASED PRODUCT.    INVESTIGATION: JAY COUSSENS, DAN MATHEWSON, AND JACK FARMER WERE ON LOCATION AT APPROXIMATELY 7:30PM. THEY TOOK PICTURES OF THE SPILL AND SPOKE WITH PHIL JAMES. DAN MATHEWSON CONDUCTED AN INVESTIGATION INTO THE CAUSE OF THE MECHANICAL FAILURE ON THE TRUCK. DAN STATED THAT "IT WOULD BE VERY DIFFICULT TO DETERMINE EXACTLY WHAT HAPPENED BUT DUE TO THE EXTENSIVE DAMAGE THAT IT WAS MOST LIKELY DRIVER ERROR, IN THE FORM OF IMPROPER SHIFTING, WHICH CAUSED THE DRIVELINE THE SHEER OFF. HE DISCOVERED THAT NOT ONLY WAS THE DRIVELINE SHEERED OFF BUT THE U JOINT, DIFFERENTIAL, AND THE YOLK WERE BROKEN AS WELL. IN HIS OPINION THE ONLY WAY THAT THIS COULD HAPPEN IS IMPROPER SHIFTING AT SPEED. DAN ALSO STATED THAT THE U JOINT WOULD BE PART OF A DRIVER'S PRE-TRIP INSPECTION AND IF IT WAS CRACKED PRIOR TO STARTING THE SHIFT PHIL WOULD HAVE NOTICED. DAN CONTINUED STATING THAT A DRIVER WOULD BE ABLE TO NOTICE DAMAGE TO HIS DRIVE LINE WHILE IN TRANSIT SO THE DAMAGE MOST LIKELY WAS CAUSED AFTER THE TRIP BEGAN. HOWEVER DUE TO THE NATURE OF THIS INCIDENT A SPECIFIC CAUSE OF THE MECHANICAL FAILURE CANNOT BE DETERMINED.
column169: ACTION ITEMS/CONCLUSIONS: ALL DRIVERS WILL HAVE THE IMPORTANCE OF A THOROUGH PRE-TRIP INSPECTION COMMUNCATION TO THEM. DRIVERS WILL ALSO BE COUNSELED ON THE PROPER SHIFTING TECHNIQUES IN ORDER TO PREVENT MECHANICAL FAILURES OF THIS NATURE IN THE FUTURE.    AFTER THE INCIDENT A REVIEW OF PHIL JAMES RECORD WAS TRIGGERED WITH THE COMPANY. DUE TO A VARIETY OF PAST INCIDENTS, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT PHIL JAMES DOES NOT MEET THE QUALITY OF DRIVER THAT ROLFSON OIL SEEKS TO EMPLOY. HIS EMPLOYMENT WAS TERMINATED WITH ROLFSON OIL ON 10/22/2014.

column43: UNDYED ULTRA LOW SULFER DIESEL  DYED ULTRA LOW SULFER DIESEL
column168: ON 10/27/14 AT 4:30AM CST OUR DRIVER TOOK HIS EYES OFF THE ROAD AND OVERTURNED ON THE CUMBERLAND PARKWAY. THE VEHICLE OVERTURNED INTO THE MEDIAN WHERE IT CAME TO REST UP-SIDE DOWN. AT THAT TIME TWO MAN HOLE COVERS STARTED TO DRIP AND RELEASE SMALL QUANTITIES OF OUR CARGO (ULTRA LOW SULFER DIESEL). THE RELEASE CONTINUED UNTIL PECCO ENVIRONMENTAL ARRIVED ON SITE TO TIGHTEN THE MAN HOLES. THIS TIME PERIOD WAS APPROXIMATELY 2 1/2 HOURS. TOTAL RELEASE WAS LESS THAN 200 GALLONS. ALL CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS REMOVED AND GRASS SEED SOWED. NO OTHER CONTAMINATION WAS EVIDENT. NO-ONE WAS INJURED.
column169: ALL DRIVERS WERE BOUGHT IN FOR A ONE-ON-ONE REMIDER OF THE DANGERS OF DISTRACTED DRIVING. ALSO, THE DESTROYED TRACTOR AND TRAILER WAS PARKED AT OUR TERMINAL FOR ALL DRIVERS TO SEE. THIS HELPED TO SOLIDIFY THE DANGERS OF DISTRACTED DRIVING.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column62: Conveyer or Material Handling Equipment Mishap
column168: ON OCT 27, 2014 AN UNAUTHORIZED DISCHARGE OF 2600 GALLONS OF GASOLINE SPILLED FROM OUR TRAILER WHEN A CONNECTING PIPE TO A COMPARTMENT BROKE.  THE DISCHARGE LASTED LESS THAN FIVE MINUTES.  IMMEDIATELY, THE LA STATE POLICE WERE CONTACTED AS WELL AS THE BATON ROUGE FIRE DEPARTMENT.  THE REMAINING 4 COMPARTMENTS ON THE TRAILER WERE NOT COMPROMISED.  THE DRIVER HIT THE EMERGENCY SHUT OFF VALVE ON THE TRAILER, BUT DUE TO THE LOCATION OF THE PIPE, ALL THE PRODUCT IN THAT COMPARTMENT SPILLED AND THERE WAS NOTHING THAT COULD BE DONE.  THE DIRE DEPARTMENT SPRAYED FOAM AND THE CLEANUP CONTRACTOR, UNITED STATES ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES DEPLOYED BOOMS TO CONTAIN THE SPILL UNTIL THEY COULD CLEANUP.
column169: NO CAUSE FOR THE SPILL COULD BE FOUND BY ANY OF THE AUTHORITIES ON THE SCENE, BUT IT DID APPEAR SOMETHING HAD STRUCK THE PIPE CAUSING THE FAILURE.  WE HAVE INTRODUCED TRAINING TO ALL DRIVERS TO PROACTIVELY LOOK FOR ANYTHING ON THE VEHICLES AS WELL AS IN THE ROADWAY THAT COULD HIT THE TRAILER WHILE IN TRANSIT.

UNIT 1'S AREA OF REST WAS APPROX. 120 FEET NORTH AND APPROX. 15 FEET EAST OF THE AREA OF IMPACT.      (DRIVER DESCRIPTION)    I WAS TRAVELING NORTH BOUND ON 18 AND AS I ENTERED INTO A CURVE, I ENCOUNTERED TRAFFIC IN THE SOUTHBOUND LANE, PARTICULARLY A PICK WITH A TRAILER ATTACHED WAS CLSOE TO THE CENTER YELLOW LINE AND I MOVED SLIGHTLY TO MY RIGHT TO ENSURE THAT WE BOTH COULD PASS SAFELY WITH OUR TRAILERS. column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column168: THATCHER TRANSPORTATION'S DRIVER, DON DEAN, SENSED SOMETHING WAS WRONG WITH THE TRUCK AND/OR TRAILER AND PULLED OVER NEXT TO THE CURTISS SERVICE CENTER, 12742 HIGHWAY 200, IN SIMMS, MONTANA.    WHILE CHECKING OUT THE EQUIPMENT HE NOTICED AN IBC (TOTE) OF SULFURIC ACID LEAKING FROM A CRACKED SEAM ON THE CONTAINER.  HE CALLED HIS SUPERVISOR IN SALT LAKE CITY AND WAS TOLD TO SPREAD SODA ASH AROUND TO PREVENT THE SPREAD OF MATERIAL, WHICH HE DID.    TOM LIND, OUR GLENDIVE, MONTANA PLANT MANAGER WAS ASKED TO RESPOND BY THE PRESIDENT OF THE COMPANY AND, IN THE MEANTIME, THE LOCAL VOLUNTEER FIRE DEPARTMENT BROUGHT A LOAD OF SAND TO THE SCENE, WHICH WAS SPREAD AROUND TO CREATE A BERM.    TOM LIND SPREAD THE SODA ASH THAT HE HAD BROUGHT FROM OUR GLENDIVE PLANT AROUND AND MIXED IN UNTIL THE PH WAS BROUGHT UP TO 7 (NEUTRAL) AND THE MATERIAL NEUTRALIZED.  AFTER NEUTRALIZING THE MATERIAL, HE SCOOPED IT INTO CONTAINERS AND HAULED IT BACK TO OUR PLANT IN GLENDIVE.    THE OWNERS OF CURTISS SERVICE CENTER, SATISFIED THE SAND WAS COMPLETELY NEUTRALIZED BASED ON THE PH TESTS, ASKED IF THEY COULD HAVE IT.  VINCE KOLAR, THE EMERGENCY MANAGER FIRE WARDEN OF CASCADE COUNTY GAVE HIS APPROVAL AND THE REMAINING SAND WAS MOVED TO THEIR PROPERTY BY TRACTOR.
column169: EVEN THOUGH THE IBC HAD BEEN TESTED ONLY WEEKS BEFORE IT FAILED, THE IBC THAT CRACKED WAS SEVEN YEARS OLD AND PROBABLY WAS SUFFERING FROM MATERIAL FATIGUE THAT WAS HASTENED BY THE VIBRATIONS DURING TRANSIT.    WE HAVE DETERMINED THAT WE WILL TAKE EVERY IBC OUT OF SERVICE AFER FIVE YEARS, GOING FORWARD, IN ORDER TO PREVENT MATERIAL FATIGUE FROM REACHING A CRITICALITY POINT.

column169: Incident reported late due to the following:   Shipments are entered into HTC operating system, TMW, and the carrier’s safety program down loads information from the operating system on all first alerts. Manager reversed the loading sequence showing TURBOCHARGE II NP (HIGH ALKALINE LIQUID LAUNDRY BREAK) [Sodium Hydroxide Solution] in compartment 1 and TCX-0L104 [Not Regulated] in compartment 3; Compartment 2 was empty.     When spill was reported it was reported as a release at the end of loading from compartment 3 which shows a non-regulated material and a report was not completed. On March 30, 2015 it was discover that the shipments were loaded exactly opposite, TCX-0L104 [Not Regulated] in compartment 1 and TURBOCHARGE II NP (HIGH ALKALINE LIQUID LAUNDRY BREAK) [Sodium Hydroxide Solution] in compartment 3.     We do not believe that this has happened before this occurrence. However , we will review this locations reports and if any other discrepancies are discovered corrections will be made.

column168: CSX Intermodal personnel at the Charlotte NC Terminal discovered PACU893116, released approximately 10gals from rear and underneath container onto asphalt pavement.  The container is a load of NA1993, Combustible Liquids NOS (cyclosiloxane), Combustible Liquid, PG III in 300gal plastic totes in metal cages. The container was isolated and shipper, Pacer Stacktrain Inc, Jan Perry, 614-923-2037, 6805 Perimeter Drive, Dublin, OH 43016, was notified by CSX Intermodal Cust Svc. The Charlotte NC Fire Dept, the NC Dept of Environmental/Natural Resources, and the NRC were notified.  Hepaco Environmental, CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found one 300gal tote (approx.) released approx. 10gals of product due to puncture from rubbing against metal.  The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper. Contractor personnel transferred product from damaged tote into new tote, deconned spilled areas and remaining freight, and cleaned up the material. The original freight container with proper load/block/brace was released to the shipper.     This incident did not require a special switching move.  This incident did not require a Form 7.1.
column169: Notified shipper to refer to the Intermodal Loading Guide for proper loading and blocking/bracing methods.

While offloading flight 502 in SNA, Southwest Airlines’ Employees reported discovering a cardboard box with spillable battery markings that had been contaminated with a liquid. The battery was associated with a Customers wheelchair per 49 CFR 175.10(a)(16) and packed by a trained Southwest Airlines Employee.

column168: ON FRIDAY, OCTOBER 3, 2014 AT APPROXIAMATELY 2:31AM, THE DRIVER OF A 2004 ACURA MDX WAS TRAVELING NORTHBOUND ON PORT ST., AGAINST TRAFFIC APPROACHING THE INTERSECTION WITH N CLAIBOURNE AVE. AT THE SAME TIME, A 2012 KENWORTH TRACTOR PULLIN A 2012 POLAR TANKER TRAILER HAULING GASOLINE WAS TRAVELING WESTBOUND ON N CLAIBOURNE AVE. APPROACHING PORT ST. WHEN VEHICLES ON AND TWO COLLIDED IN THE INTERSECTION. AFTERWARDS, THE ACURA VEERED OFFROAD AND CAME TO REST IN THE REAR PARKING LOT OF A GAS STATION. THE KENWORTH VEERED OFF ROAD ALSO STRUCK A STATIONARY SIGN BEFORE CATCHING FIRE. AFTER COLLIDING WITH THE STATIONARY SIGN, THE DRIVER OF THE KENWORTH WAS UNABLE TO ESCAPE HIS BURNING VEHICLE AND WAS PRONOUNCED DEAD ON THE SCENE AFTERWARDS. DRIVER OF THE ACURA MANAGED TO EXIT HER VEHICLE AFTER IMPACT AND WAS CHARGED WITH NEGLIGENT HOMICIDE AFTERWARDS.
column169: THIS WAS A CRASH THAT WAS NON-PREVENTABLE ON THE PART OF THE DRIVER AND CARRIER.

column168: ON OCTOBER 30TH 2014, DRIVER RICHARD SKIDMORE ATTEMPTED TO UNLOAD A 2000 GALLON COMARTMENT OF GASOLINE INTO TANKS AT VALLEY EXXON IN STANLEY, VA.    AFTER MAKING HIS CONNECTIONS, HE OPENED THE VALVE TO THE COMPARTMENT TO BEGIN UNLOADING. A COUPLING BETWEEN BELLY VALVE AND DISCHARGE FITTING RUPTURED SENDING A SPRAY OF GASOLINE.    DRIVER TOOK IMMEDIATE ACTION AND CLOSED VALVE TO COMPARTMENT, PREVENTING FURTHER LIQUID FROM ESCAPING.    SOMEONE HAD CALLED 911    TRUCK WAS PARKED ON LEVEL GROUND AND SPILL WAS CONTAINED WITH SPILL PADS AND ABSORBENT MATERIAL ON TRUCK BY THE DRIVER AND STORE EMPLOYEES.    A REPAIRMAN WAS DISPATACHED TO FIX BROKEN COUPLING, BUT UPON HIS ARRIVAL SAFETY PERSONAL ON SCENE WOULD NOT ALLOW HIM TO FIX ON SITE.    ANOTHER TRUCK WAS DISPATCHED TO OFF LOAD COMPARTMENT WITH PRODUCT STILL ON TRUCK.    A HAZ MAT CREW WAS DISPATCHED TO OVERSEE TRANSFER OF PRODUCT FROM ONE TRUCK TO ANOTHER.    IT WAS REPORTED BY NEWS MEDIA THAT 50 GALLONS WAS SPILLED. INVENTORY RECORDS (SEE ATTACHMENT) AND IN MY OPINION BY BEING ON SITE AND HAVING 30 YEARS EXPERIENCE IN THE BUSINESS, THAT ONLY SERVERAL GALLONS AT MOST WERE LOST.    R KEITH LASWON  VICE PRESIDENT
column169: TANKER WAS TAKEN BACK TO SHOP. REPAIRED AND PUT BACK INTO SERVICE.
